				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">By &quot;jittery scanline&quot;, do you refer to the artifact above Shadow Man that <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Game_bugs" class="postlink">the wiki page describes</a>?</div><br /><br />Yes.  My emulator shared that same effect with FCEUX and Nestopia if I introduced the aforementioned hack.<br /><br />I did some logging to record the registers for which the menu screen accesses.  During VBlank, it writes to the IRQ latch register, setting the reload value to 88 and then it commits that by writing to the IRQ Reload register.  This establishes the first scroll break on scanline 88.<br /><br />On scanline 88, it writes to the IRQ latch register, setting the reload value to 64.  It's an attempt to setup the second scroll break, but it never calls the IRQ Reload register.  Consequentially, the second scroll break appears in the wrong position.<br /><br />It's possible that my timing is sufficiently off that the Reload register write does not get a chance to run.  But, it's not an issue with the mapper incorrectly handling the register calls since there is no record that Reload was called at all on scanline 88.<br /><br />When the IRQ counter hits 0, I assume it is supposed to automatically reset it to the reload value.  In this case, it gets 88 again before the 64 was set.  It could be a race condition like that.  But, why would the programmers take such a risk and not call the IRQ Reload register to commit the 64 value?</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

